#+LATEX: \clearpage
* Summary

** Rationale

As declared by the Dutch government and validated by multiple surveys, social isolation among senior citizens (abbreviated as 'seniors') is an increasing problem. It lowers the quality of life and threatens the well-being of a large part of our population. This project connects complexity science theory and social capital theory. It uses both as the starting point for developing, guiding, and evaluating a design thinking innovation of social health games. The overall aim is to use these social health games to decrease loneliness amongst seniors. As a preparatory step for the trial in which we will evaluate the effectiveness of the games, the aims in this study are to validate the measurement of social interaction and examine the feasibility of the gaming portal.

** Objective

The overarching project aims to assess whether e-gaming can become an effective intervention in lessening social loneliness and emotional loneliness in seniors. This protocol's specific objective is to present a feasibility and validity study that addresses the following two aims:

- *Aim 1:* To assess whether gaming-related social interactions in networks of seniors can be validly monitored using time-series of playing behavior?

- *Aim 2:* To get feedback on the feasibility and appreciation of the gaming portal.

** Study population

The study population consists of 100 Dutch-speaking participants aged 65+. These participants are kept as diverse as possible regarding educational level, degree of mobility, marital status, and whether they live independently or in a home. Family and friends of the participants and other people not meeting these inclusion criteria are welcome to use the portal and form a pool of people that the participants can play with. This pool will be tracked within the gaming portal and posed some questions regarding their fellow players and their social capital; they will not be asked to complete questionnaires.

** Intervention

Participants are invited to download and use an app that functions as a portal. The portal provides access to several different games that stimulate social interaction. Participants will be asked to play at least twice a week but may play as often as they like.

** Study design

A validation and feasibility study using prospective observational data supported by qualitative structured interviews and social network analyses.

** Main study parameters

In the validity study, the gaming-related social interaction will be compared against a standardized social network measure. In the feasibility study, the main outcomes are participants' experiences with the games and portal and questionnaire completion rates. 

** Method

Participants will complete questionnaires on both online and offline social networks, loneliness, health, and well-being at baseline and study completion after three months of gameplay. The loneliness questionnaire will be repeated every month. Questions about gaming-related social interactions will be asked at the end of each game session. Concurrent validity will be examined by comparing gaming-related social interaction with the standardized measure of social networks. Construct validity will be assessed by testing four hypotheses on correlations between gaming-related social interaction, loneliness, and enjoyment. Feasibility is evaluated by inviting a random sample of participants who played a lot (n=10) or little (n=10) for telephone interviews to ask about their experiences with the games and portal. Additionally, completion rates of questionnaires and missing data on items will be checked to assess adherence.
# Participants are interviewed at the beginning of their participation to elucidate their social network using questions from the Longitudinal Aging Study Amsterdam (SN-LASA) and are asked to fill in The Older Persons and Informal Caregivers Survey (TOPICS). Then, there are three in-game moments of assessment. Firstly, participants are prompted to fill in a survey on the first login, reminiscent of a profile page. This questionnaire entails the Life Space Questionnaire (LSQ), the DeJong Gierveld 11 item Loneliness Scale (DJG), and to provide more information regarding Social Capital and themselves. Secondly, before gameplay, they will be prompted to answer questions about the other participant(s) with whom they had not played with before. These questions are adopted from the SN-LASA and are designed to gain information about the relationship between players. Finally, after gameplay, both participants are presented with a short questionnaire about their experience regarding their fellow player(s). Duration of session and gameplay, contact timestamps, and game performance are also stored on a per-game basis.

** Nature and extent of the burden and risks associated with participation, benefit, and group relatedness

The risks for the participants is low. All data will be collected using online surveys and are kept anonymous. At the end of the trial, only some participants will be invited to complete semi-structured telephone interviews. They are then asked to provide information such as their name and phone number. No sensitive questions are asked. This intervention is not associated with any more risk than that of playing popular online games such as wordfeud. Reducing feelings of loneliness (both subjective and objective) could be one of the benefits of participation.

#+LATEX: \clearpage
* Introduction and rationale

As declared by The Dutch government and validated by multiple surveys, social isolation among senior citizens (abbreviated as 'seniors') is an increasing problem, lowering the quality of life and threatening the well-being of a large part of our population. Moreover, it is a major driver of societal expenses for health care and welfare organizations. Currently, 1 in 4 seniors feels lonely, summing up to more than 1 million seniors with feelings of social isolation, of whom 200,000 are seriously complaining of loneliness cite:ouderenpact,TNONIPOetc. 

This problem warrants social and political action, and urgently asks for interdisciplinary complexity science research because social isolation and the linked subjective loneliness are complex societal problems. They are the net outcome of social network changes during aging, directly depending on multiple factors, such as impairments in hearing, cognition, mobility, the availability of family members and friends, the opportunities for transportation, etc. cite:shiovitz201330,van1990size,litwin2014confidant. Seniors' social networks behave as complex adaptive systems because of the multi-scale interplay of several interacting causal factors and their positive feedback loops. For example, depressed feelings and cognitive decline limit social interactions, causing a lack of positive events, and thereby further lowering mood and cognition over time cite:boulton2015embracing,loscalzo2017network.     

Expected socio-cultural and demographic changes, such as the growing number of single seniors, will have a high impact. Adding further to the problem's complexity is the finding that social isolation, independent from mental health (e.g., depression), is also cross-linked with the immune system, causing lower resistance and resilience for infections and, finally, increased mortality cite:snyder2016social,braithwaite2018complexity. In conclusion, social isolation has an increasing burden on individual and population levels and asks for better understanding and innovative action at micro-, meso- and macro-level. 

This project connects complexity science theory and social capital theory and uses both as the starting point for developing, guiding, and evaluating a design thinking innovation of social health games.
# 1. In this project's context, the adjective "complex" for the problem of loneliness refers to senior social networks:
#    1. act as multi-component complex adaptive systems
#    2. have many (feedback) interactions
#    3. are at least partly non-linear
#    4. are history and environment-dependent
#    5. are of different temporal and spatial scales
#    Based on this pivotal theoretical notion, we will use three modes of investigation of social behavior by working with complexity science: experimental, computational, and theoretical.
# 2. We rely on Social Capital Theory (SCT) because it integrates the strengths of psychological and economic consumer/household theories. SC predicts that seniors start using inter-generational games when their social and personal goals can be met in-game.    
# 3. The design thinking methodology of iterative and cyclic working on innovation, directly in contact with the end-users, will be applied throughout the creative process.     

This scientific study will be based on complexity science methods such as dynamical network analyses, computational modeling of social resilience, and tipping point monitoring. Although it will not be based on the Research Through Design methods, they will be used in the development phase.

As a preparatory step for the trial in which we will evaluate the effectiveness of the games, the aims in this study are to validate the measurement of social interaction and examine the feasibility of the gaming portal.
# To assess that these aims are achievable, we must validate whether social games can function as tools to measure social interaction. This study will be the first formal exploration of the usability, feasibility, and validity of social health games to monitor social interaction and reduce loneliness in the older population. This study will use a single portal that presents two different games: one that invokes and measures social interaction and a control game that utilizes single-player gameplay. We hypothesize that the social gaming portal will be able to measure social interaction sufficiently (e.g., has a positive correlation with a validated means of measuring social interaction) and that the social game will be played more frequently compared to the control game.

#+LATEX: \clearpage
* Objectives

# As this is a collaborative study with multiple parties involved, it will contain two different objectives. These objectives are aimed at the validation of the measurement method (i.e., measuring social interaction through gameplay) and the feasibility of this study. Validation is divided into two categories, concurrent validity and construct validity. 
The objectives are as follows:

** Concurrent validity

- To examine the concurrent validity of social interaction measured with virtual gaming against social interaction measured with the domain-contact method in older adults participating in a social gaming intervention.

** Construct validity

- To examine the degree to which data from the social gaming intervention can be used to validly measure social interaction in older adults. 
  
** Feasibility

- To examine participants’ willingness to complete monthly questionnaires on loneliness and social capital by evaluating completion rates.
- To find an appropriate frequency for assessing loneliness and social capital.
- To assess the participant’s experiences and identify barriers and enablers to gameplay and use of the portal.
- To evaluate the recruitment strategy.
- To gain insight into with whom our participants tend to play with most (i.e., known vs. unknown players, people of similar age vs. younger).

* Study population

** Population (base)

The study population consists of 100 Dutch-speaking participants aged 65+. These participants are kept as diverse as possible regarding educational level, degree of mobility, marital status, and whether they live independently or in a home. Family and friends of the participants and other people not meeting these inclusion criteria are welcome to use the portal and will form a pool of people that the participants can play with. This pool will be tracked within the gaming portal and posed some questions regarding their fellow players and their social capital; they will not be asked to complete questionnaires or partake in interviews outside of the gaming portal.

Participants are recruited from existing networks associated with the three parties involved, as well as through ads in the local newspaper. Existing networks being: Facebook and other social networking platforms, Netwerk 100, healthcare institutions, home care providers, advertisements or articles in local newspapers, libraries, etc.

** Sample size calculation

This study is mainly focused on determining whether social interaction can be measured via gaming. Concurrent validity is assessed by correlating the method employed by the game to the validated questionnaire, as provided by the SN-LASA study[fn:1]. To compute the needed sample size, we made use of a commonly used correlation sample size calculation cite:hulley2013designing as a correlation between two methods is applied. The sample size calculation used the following parameters:

$$\alpha=0.05,\ \beta=0.2,\ r=0.3$$

Parameter $r$, the expected correlation coefficient, is set to $0.3$. It is the lowest expected correlation for the hypotheses that will test the construct validity. I.e., we expect a weak but statistically significant correlation between social interaction and loneliness.

The calculation yields a total of *85 participants* needed for this study. To account for participant dropout, 20% was added on top of the 85 participants required, bringing the total of participants up to 102. We believe that this number is also feasible, practically speaking. The 20% dropout rate is based on another comparable study in a similar population (cite:konstantinidis2014design).

* Intervention

Participants are invited to download and use an app that functions as a portal. The portal provides access to several different games that stimulate social interaction. These games are centered around both asynchronous communication (i.e., games that connect players but don't require simultaneous play) and synchronous gameplay (i.e., games that connect players and require simultaneous play). For example, one game challenges players to share photos of items that start with a particular letter. The following player shares a photo beginning with the last letter of the previous player's item, and so on. 

Modes of communication will be; voice message, texting, and sending photos and videos. All games will be available to play from the beginning. Participants will be advised to play at least twice a week but may play as often as they like. This advice ensures that participants give the game a try, without making it compulsory as we are interested in the natural behavior of participants. This gaming portal is, in itself, both the measuring method and the intervention.
# Participants are required to download an app that functions as a portal providing two different games: one that invokes and measures social interaction and a control game that utilizes single-player gameplay. Both games will be free to play from the beginning, though the advice is to play at least two times per week. This advice ensures that participants give the game a chance, while it is non-binding as the natural behavior is of interest. The control game is added to provide extra diversity in the gaming portal to entice participants into playing more. This gaming portal is, in itself, both the measuring method as the intervention.

* Study design

This study is a prospective observational study supported by qualitative structured interviews and social network analyses.

** Outcome measures and assessments

*** Questionnaires

This study utilizes several different questionnaires to measure different constructs. Here we provide an overview and their respective abbreviations that will henceforth be used.

