*** Timing of data collection

There are two types of assessments in this study: information gathered within the gaming portal, and information gathered using semi-structured telephone interviews. This section will elaborate on both types and their respective timing (see figure ref:fig:timeline). 

At baseline, participants will be interviewed regarding their entire social network through the SN-LASA method, and their physical and mental health and well-being will be inquired through the TOPICS-SF. At the end of the study, well-being will again be asked through the TOPICS questionnaire. Furthermore, the SN-LASA method will be applied again for the whole network and the gaming-related network, followed by qualitative questions regarding participants' experiences using the gaming portal. 

During the study, the game portal will be opened for participants to play games. Information gathering within the social games brings about three different timings of assessment within the portal. First, on the first login, the DJG and LSQ will be presented with more questions regarding personal information (PI). The DJG will henceforth be repeated monthly. Second, whenever two players that have not played together before are matched, a questionnaire is presented asking about their relationship. Third, after gameplay, automatically generated data is saved, and questions regarding the participants' perception of their perception of social interaction are displayed. The whole study will take three months. The questions posed in the second and third timing will also be asked to the pool of players consisting of friends, family, and others interested in playing.

#+NAME: fig:timeline
#+CAPTION: Timeline of this study regarding the timing of questionnaires.
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 1\textwidth :placement [t!]
[[./timeline.png]]

*** Data collection
**** *Beginning of the trial*

Outside of the gaming portal, participants within the main group are asked to answer two questionnaires at the start of trial participation. These questionnaires are TOPICS and SN-LASA. The pool consisting of friends, family, and others, will not be invited for these interviews outside of the gaming portal. 


_Constructs Measured_:

1. Social networks, by the SN-LASA.
2. Physical and mental health and well-being by the TOPICS.

**** *Information gathered in the gaming portal*

***** First and last login in the game


At the first and last login of the trial, the game prompts the participant to answer questions that set up the account and fill in the requisite additional information consisting of further questionnaires. The questions posed can be found in appendix ref:sec:per_user. The participant will be given three questionnaires combined similar to setting up a profile on any social networking platform. Questionnaires posed are the LSQ, DJG, and part of the SN-LASA, together with questions related to the participant's situation. However, this profile is not entirely visible to others as it contains information of a personal nature.


_Constructs measured_:

1. Life Space, by the LSQ.
2. Loneliness, by the DJG.
3. Social networks, by part of SN-LASA.


***** Pre-gameplay


In each session, whenever a participant engages with others in a game, there are two possibilities. The participants have played together before, in which case gameplay is as usual. Alternatively, participants have not encountered one another within the gaming portal. In which case, both are asked to provide additional information on the nature of their relationship. In appendix ref:sec:per_new, we depict these questions. Each user is posed with ten multiple-choice questions and three questions that require integer input. These questions are either directly taken from the SN-LASA or SC.


_Constructs measured_:

1. Social networks, by part of SN-LASA.
2. Social capital, by SC.


***** Post-gameplay


After each session, all participants are asked questions regarding their perception of social interaction with the other participant(s). Furthermore, the information generated automatically through gameplay is stored. In appendix ref:sec:per_game, the variables are shown that correspond with the session. Three multiple-choice questions are posed regarding their experience towards the other player, while the rest of the data in the table is automatically generated. Upon an asynchronous game design, timestamps of each communicative transaction are saved. Depending on which game is being played, the final scores are stored. Furthermore, the session's duration is stored (i.e., from game initiation to one user leaving the game), and the length of the game itself is being logged. This difference illustrates the time being used to communicate after the game has been terminated (e.g., participants can choose to stay in the session to keep talking even when the game is finished).


_Constructs measured_:

1. Social networks, by part of SN-LASA.

**** *End of trial*

After the trial, all members of the main group are asked to answer the SN-LASA again in an interview over the phone. Some members of the main group will be selectively invited to participate in structured interviews over the phone about their experiences with the game. These interviews are regarding some of the feasibility aspects of this study, shown in appendix ref:sec:kwantint. All members of the main group are asked to answer the SN-LASA again, employing an interview.


_Constructs Measured_:

1. Social networks, by the SN-LASA.
2. Well-being by the TOPICS.


# *** Feasibility study
# 
# - How was the communication during gameplay perceived?
#   - What makes this moment of social interaction something that is perceived as _valuable_?
#   - What is the impact on feelings of loneliness or the amount of social contacts?
# 
# Each week a questionnaire is presented to obtain information regarding feasibility. The following data will be obtained:
# 
# 
# *Qualitative questions:*
#   - How do older people perceive the games?
#   - Do push notifications actually help play more or are they perceived to be a nuisance?
#     - How many push notifications is to much?
#   - Would the player be willing to pay for such a game?
#   - What would be a good frequency for questionnaires?
# 
# 
# *Quantitative questions:*
#   - Usability, applicability and appreciation
#     - Measured by use of Likert Scales
# 
# *** Other measurements
# 
# Each week, a questionnaire is presented through a push-notification regarding to subjective experiences that are designed to measure or obtain the following information:
# 
# - Did the player already know the other person in real life?
#   - What kind of relation is it (parental, neighbourly, etc.)?
#   - How well do the players know one another?
#   - Is the relationship a positive one?
# 
# Further information of interest that will be obtained on a per-game basis:
# 
# - Game performance and results.
#   - Depending on game design, this could be used to increase game difficulty depending on performance such that gaming itself would be more engaging, keeping the game from being regarded as "boring" or "easy".
# - Changes in reaction speed, insights, qualities
# 
# 
# Further information that is needed asked to the participants:
# 
# - Age [fn:1].
# - TOPICS (*TODO uitwerken*)
#

* Main study parameters/endpoints

In the validity study, the gaming-related social interaction will be compared against a standardized measure of the social network. In the feasibility study, the main outcomes are participants’ experiences with the games and portal and questionnaire completion rates.

* Method

** Concurrent validity

Concurrent validity is demonstrated when a test has a high correlation with another, previously validated, measure. It is the evidence to which we defend the use of our method for predicting outcomes of the construct being social interaction. Social interaction is measured as a function of social network measures (e.g., connectivity) and answers to the questions posed in appendix tables ref:tab:per_new_user and ref:tab:per_game (noted with the tag SI in the "USED FOR" column). Social networks are usually measured for the overall network, but it will be also be assessed for the gaming-related network to approximate the gaming-related conditions. In our case, we shall correlate the participants' social gaming network, unveiled by employing the SN-LASA study method, to their social gaming network generated by the interactions within the gaming portal.

** Construct validity

Construct validity can be viewed as the degree to which a test measures what it claims to be measuring. To assume construct validity, we will make use of a set of validation statements unto which our method will be tested. The rule of thumb is that at least $\approx 75\%$ of these hypotheses must be correct.

1. Social loneliness (calculated from DJG) is correlated with the number of social interactions ($r>0.3$).
2. Correlation between emotional loneliness and the number of social interactions is less strong, then the correlation between social loneliness and the number of social interactions.
3. "Connectivity" is higher between those with strong ties than those with weak ties[fn:2].
4. People who enjoy playing games with others will play for a longer duration in games that invoke social interaction than those that do not.

** Feasibility study
:PROPERTIES:
:ID:       F5205AD9-0EE9-4C6F-8FF7-1488B2179DED
:END:

This study also consists of assessing the feasibility of the more extensive comprehensive study. It is designed in such a way that we can obtain answers to the following aims:

- To examine participants’ willingness to complete monthly questionnaires on loneliness and social capital by evaluating completion rates.
- To find an appropriate frequency for assessing loneliness and social capital.
- To assess the participant’s experiences and identify barriers and enablers to gameplay and use of the portal.
- To evaluate the recruitment strategy.
- To gain insight into with whom our participants tend to play with most (i.e., known vs. unknown players, people of similar age vs. younger).

** Data management and collection
label:sec_dat_col

Participant data is collected anonymously. Only participants selected to participate in the semi-structured interviews after the study will be approached within the gaming portal to provide their name and phone number. This personal data is stored in a separate encrypted database and removed one year after research finalization. All collected data will be streamed from gameplay at each gaming session to an ISO 9001, 27001, and NEN 7510 certified database. From this database, a weekly data transfer will occur to a Radboudumc database in the Digital Research Environment (DRE), where all data are exclusively accessible and processed by investigators in this project and is saved within the Netherlands. Data will be stored for a total of 15 years after the publication of the related paper. The gaming portal, together with data gathering, will be disabled after the completion of data collection. 

** Analysis

The construct validity hypotheses are tested using Pearson correlation (H1, H2) or T-tests (H3, H4) or their non-parametric equivalent if outcomes are not normally distributed. Concurrent validity will be analyzed by estimating the correlation between gaming-related social networks, generated by interactions within the gaming portal, and gaming-related social networks (SN-LASA). The study's feasibility questions will be answered using descriptive statistics to describe the sample characteristics and questionnaire completion rates. We will also examine the variation in loneliness over time to inform the preferred frequency of completing the questionnaire. 
# Hypotheses regarding construct validity are tested using correlation or regression models, depending on the outcome. The SN-LASA network characteristics will be correlated to the features of the social gaming network using correlation or regression models, depending on the result of measurements. The study's feasibility questions will be answered by descriptive statistics and the number of missing values to see whether participants are willing to complete the repeated questionnaires. We will also test whether there is a difference in loneliness about the various measurements (repeated measures ANOVA if the assumptions are met).

